emale stereotypes—demure maiden or disruptive shrew—prevalent in writings of the period. Because nearly all of the texts were written by men but addressed to women, they exhibit a fascinating interplay between male views of so-called women's literature and the demands of their intended audience. Familiarity with this widely read genre is essential to a full understanding of medieval culture, and Chaste Passions is an excellent introduction to these often racy, sometimes comic, tales  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian legendszEngland. 0aChristian women martyrsvLegends. 0aChristian women saintsvLegends. 0aVirginityxReligious aspectsxChristianityvLegends. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies.  aChristian female saints .  aChristian legends .  aChristian saints .  aChristian women martyrs .  aChristianity .  aChristianity studies .  aEnglish Virgin Martyr.  aMedieval English Virgin Martyr Legends.  aMedieval literature .  aMedieval stories .  aMedieval studies .  aMedieval writings .  aVirgin Martyr Legends.  aVirgin Martyr legends .  aVirgin Martyr mythology .  aVirgin Martyr saints .  aVirgin Martyr stories .  aVirgin Martyr tales .  aVirgin Martyrs legends .  aVirgin Martyrs literature .  aVirgin Martyrs poems .  aVirgin Martyrs prose .  aVirgin Martyrs.  achristian women legends .  afemale legends .  afemale martyrdom .  afemale stereotypes.  ahistory of Christianity.  alife of a saint .  alives of saints .  amartyrdom of the early medieval ages.  amartyrdom.  amedieval literary criticism .  amedieval martyr legends.  amedieval saints.  areligious historical texts.  areligious virginity .  arenaissance literary criticism .  arenaissance literature .  arenaissance martyrs .  asaing anastasia .  asain